<TextWithNodes><Node id="0"/>Commerzbank<Node id="11"/>, <Node id="13"/>Germany<Node id="20"/>&apos;s third biggest listed bank, on <Node id="53"/>Thursday<Node id="61"/> struggled to quell takeover rumours, as investors drove the bank&apos;s stock sharply higher despite a big drop in <Node id="172"/>second quarter<Node id="186"/> profits.

The bank blamed weak global stock markets and high operating costs for the poor <Node id="277"/>second quarter<Node id="291"/>, which saw pre-tax profits fall <Node id="324"/>40 per cent<Node id="335"/> quarter on quarter to <Node id="358"/>E186m<Node id="363"/> (<Node id="365"/>$161.8m<Node id="372"/>).

It vowed to contain soaring costs and said management had approved a recruitment freeze and the cancellation of several IT projects as part of a drive to save <Node id="535"/>E240m<Node id="540"/> by the <Node id="548"/>end of the year<Node id="563"/>.

The market largely disregarded the bank&apos;s poor performance, pushing the stock 3 per higher to around E27 as takeover speculation continued to gain momentum.

Analysts said the weak results would boost the bid speculation surrounding the stock, which has been driven by takeover rumours rather than fundamentals for most of the <Node id="893"/>past year<Node id="902"/>.

In a conference call for analysts, executives dismissed reports that <Node id="974"/>Commerzbank<Node id="985"/> was in takeover talks with <Node id="1013"/>Unicredito Italiano<Node id="1032"/>, <Node id="1034"/>Italy<Node id="1039"/>&apos;s second largest bank.

They also denied that the bank&apos;s largest shareholder, <Node id="1118"/>Assicurazioni Generali<Node id="1140"/>, the Italian insurer, had increased its stake from <Node id="1192"/>10 per cent<Node id="1203"/> to <Node id="1207"/>19 per cent<Node id="1218"/>.

But officials admitted the bank, long seen as vulnerable to a takeover, was in talks with several European banks, some of which lie outside its extensive network of partnerships. &quot;We have had contact with <Node id="1426"/>Unicredito<Node id="1436"/>, <Node id="1438"/>Soci√&#169;t√&#169; G√&#169;n√&#169;rale<Node id="1458"/>, the <Node id="1464"/>Royal Bank of Scotland<Node id="1486"/>, <Node id="1488"/>ABN Amro<Node id="1496"/>, <Node id="1498"/>Den Danske Bank<Node id="1513"/>, <Node id="1515"/>BSCH of <Node id="1523"/>Spain<Node id="1528"/> and <Node id="1533"/>HSBC<Node id="1537"/>,&quot; said an official.

Bankers said the talks were understood to have centred on the possibility of partners taking stakes in specific businesses, such as asset management, which is being restructured, or <Node id="1741"/>Comdirect<Node id="1750"/>, the bank&apos;s troubled online broking subsidiary. In return potential partners might gain seats on the bank&apos;s supervisory board, the bankers said.

Analysts said the bank&apos;s poor underlying performance for the <Node id="1958"/>third quarter<Node id="1971"/> in a row had put it under renewed pressure to boost profitability.

The bank said costs, which shot up <Node id="2075"/>18 per cent<Node id="2086"/> in the <Node id="2094"/>first half<Node id="2104"/> to <Node id="2108"/>E2.909bn<Node id="2116"/> from <Node id="2122"/>E2.47bn<Node id="2129"/> a year earlier, remained a &quot;cause for concern&quot;.

It said it planned to save <Node id="2206"/>E240m<Node id="2211"/> in the <Node id="2219"/>second half of this year<Node id="2243"/>. About <Node id="2251"/>E100m<Node id="2256"/> would come from a recruitment freeze, with a further <Node id="2310"/>E140m<Node id="2315"/> coming from cuts in information technology investments.

<Node id="2373"/>Fox-Pitt, Kelton<Node id="2389"/>, the investment bank, said a big jump in non-staff costs was behind the increase in operating expenses. These included costs linked to the restructuring of businesses, euro conversion costs and expenditure on consultancies and other projects, it said.
